metadata.name: Botanical Ghosts #168
metadata.description:
This is a work about growth, impermanence and decay. Ghostly plants and flowers grow around an invisible point, but they immediately begin to fade into the dark background and are soon replaced and covered by others. This process of accumulation and disappearance builds an ever-changing floral garland, or perhaps a funeral wreath.

The monochrome vegetation is part of a fictional flora, born out of random algorithmic combinations, and does not intend to reproduce any real species. It belongs to an “artificial nature” which, like so many worlds that the computers generate for us in movies, games, and virtual reality environments, is a convincing simulation of life, but it is not actually living. AI bots, virtual assistants and non-player characters are also representatives of the uncanny realm of the not-really-alive-but-looking-like-it, which are becoming an increasingly relevant presence in our everyday lives.

These plants and flowers speak about life as a process of incessant renovation, but also about death as the background that’s always there and makes life possible. This spectral vegetation seems to thrive precisely at the verge between both worlds.
_______________


This work is animated and will adapt to any screen size. It generates a never-ending ring of algorithmic foliage, which never repeats itself, and is different for each token. The image preview is triggered after the first five plants or flowers.
Made with p5.js

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture

metadata.name: Lineage #192
metadata.description:
Lineage is a collaboration between Tim Maxwell and Twistie that attempts to bridge the gap between traditional and generative art.
256 outputs are generated using 100% JavaScript + p5js, written by Twistie, in the distinctive style of Tim Maxwell. The code tries to replicate not only the style, but also the process and inaccuracies that go into a drawing.

Each iteration has a unique title. 
All 256 rendered outputs and their respective titles will be displayed in high quality on https://twistie.org/lineage. 

10 lucky owners will have their iteration hand drawn and signed. They will each receive the physical 1/1 as well as an NFT version.

Press 's' on keyboard to save in high-res. This is how the art is intended to be viewed.

Hardware acceleration on Chromium-based browsers can impact performance!

metadata.name: Constellation Of Happiness #64
metadata.description:
Constellation Of Happiness is a collaborative art project between NFT artists Kato Trofimova and Andrew Erickson.

Feeling happy is tough this year but it'll be much easier when you get your own constellation of happiness! Using expressionistic code art, Constellation Of Happiness channels the purest festive emotions a person can experience, for example, when tasting champagne bubbles or seeing and touching confetti. All these are turned into beautiful constellations of happiness using the aesthetics of star maps and carefully brought to your NFT collection.

2022

Kato Trofimova (Latvia) is an illustrator, visual artist, and creative director known for her love of minimalistic shapes and bright palettes. In her art, Kato questions boundaries between styles and stays optimistic no matter what.

Andrew Erickson (Switzerland) is a generative artist experimenting with various abstract styles. Be it delicate monochromatic line art or colorful gradient minimalism, Andrew is very good at coding any kind of digital beauty.

Hit 'p' in live mode to save a 9922 × 14032px PNG (for printing up to A0)
Hit 's' in live mode to save a plottable SVG

10% of proceeds go to support Processing.org

metadata.name: Saṅkhāra #41
metadata.description:
🎧 CLICK/TAP FOR SOUND ON

Saṅkhāra is a portrait of symbolic consciousness in three movements.

Colorful automata represents direct experience: touch, sight, hearing, smell, taste and thought in a ceaseless flow of novelty.

The automata congeals into form alluding to the way our minds close over experience with symbolic representation, like a plastic bag coming down over a kaleidoscope of butterflies. What was free in the open air is now trapped. What was previously wild and unpredictable is now under control, frozen and communicable.

The form’s dispersal mimics the release of mental formation, the unbinding of a symbol, the letting go of a belief. It’s a visceral reflection of the process of ceasing to identify with separateness. To strain the previous metaphor, it’s the opening of the bag and letting the butterflies return to the flow of raw, boundless experience.

—

K.C. Austin
From his cockpit in the Blue Ridge Mountains K.C. Austin (aka bzor) spends his days shaping realtime software art systems of all stripes. Informed by game design, modular synths, virtual reality and consciousness research, K.C. plays shaders like a fiddle and fashions creative pipelines like a spider spins webs.

James Paterson
Fascinated by the relationship between ancient and futuristic mediums, James Paterson has been exploring a unique synthesis of drawing, code, animation and sculpture under the moniker ‘Presstube’ since 1999. Paterson draws inspiration from meditation, molecular biology, music, parenting and psychedelics - the seen, the heard, the felt, the cognized.

metadata.name: Crosswalk Monsoon #20
metadata.description:
The story behind this collection is that there isn't really a story behind this collection. It is the result of play, tinkering, and curiosity.

One of the beautiful things about generative art is how we can achieve drastically different results simply by modifying a few parameters or lines of code. As my first release here on fxhash was 'Sabler', it felt fitting that my release for #fxhashturnsone would itself be a modified version of that 'Sabler' algorithm, albeit giving drastically different results.

It is notable for the fact that this is perhaps my most 'chaotic' collection yet, letting go of carefully considered proportions, angles and positioning and here leaving that in the hands of the computer. In a way, this simple act represents several design decisions I never would have imagined myself making a year ago, highlighting my growth as a generative artist over the past year.

It is also a reflection of the inspiration gained from many of the artists and boundary-pushers in the space that each time unlock and encourage creations beyond the immediate comfort zone. For that, this is a 'Thank You' to all of you.

With that, here's to many more years of generative beauty and inspiration on fxhash and beyond.

As with previous collections, I highly recommend viewing the images at full size and savouring the details and the chaos up close. Pressing 'S' will save a 6000 x 6000 px PNG file.

50% of primary sales will be donated to the Processing Foundation.

metadata.name: Angular View #15
metadata.description:
The angle factor plays a significant role in determining how an image feels and looks.
When viewed from one angle, elements inside the frame might appear compressed and unclear, while when viewed from another angle, they might appear clear and distinct.
Choosing the right angle can encourage and guide the audience, while choosing the wrong angle can confuse and mislead him.
Therefore, when choosing the angle, one should consider aesthetic, technical, and emotional factors to present the subject to the viewer in the best light.
Depending on the angle, space and subject of the image are transformed and they can convey various meanings, including: logical visualization of space/impossible and free visualization, exaggeration and exaggeration/simplicity, stillness/movement, insider/alienation, mysterious/reliable, and complexity.
Made by p5.js
s = save

metadata.name: Balance #29
metadata.description:
(This is not just about still images, it's about sound and processes)

Balance was born from the Genuary 2023 event and the FxHash proposal to mint one "prompt" of your choice.
The chosen one was the "Generative music" prompt as an excuse to be able to explore a little the sound world that I have abandoned many years ago.

Balance is an experimental generative and interactive work that has a process of almost 3 minutes that is repeated indefinitely. The work explores the sound as matter in relation to the visual, in search of a balance in terms of sensations. As we already know, the visual has an immediate impact, while the sound, we need to dedicate more time to it. At an interactive level, you can control some actions that can enrich or ruin :) the process.

The sound is strongly influenced by composers who use granular synthesis, such as Curtis Roads. The visual parallel is represented by movement and the use of glitch aesthetics.

-----------

Balance nace a partir del evento Genuary 2023 y la propuesta de FxHash de mintear un "prompt" a elección.
El elegido fue el prompt "Generative music" como excusa poder explorar un poco el mundo sonoro que tengo abandonado hace muchos años.

Balance es un trabajo experimental generativo e interactivo que tiene un proceso de casi 3 minutos que se vuelve a repetir indefinidamente. El trabajo explora el sonido como materia en relación a lo visual, en busca de un balance en terminos de sensaciones. Como ya sabemos, lo visual tiene un impacto inmedito, en cambio lo sonoro, necesitamos dedicarle más tiempo. A nivel interactivo, se pueden controlar algunas acciones que pueden enriquezer o arruinar :) el proceso.

Lo sonoro está fuertemente influnciado por los compositores que utilizan la sintesis granular como Curtis Roads. El paralelo visual está representado por el movimiento y luego la utilización de la estética glitch.


Interactivity Keys:

[Click] -> to sound ON / OFF (remove text SOUND OFF) (be carefull if you use headphones, check levels)
(By policy, in browsers, all sounds start off muted until users interact)
[1 or Q] -> sound ON / OFF (remove text SOUND OFF) (be carefull if you use headphones, check levels)
[2 or W] -> smooth fx ON/OFF.
[3 or E] -> loop/noLoop - Play/Pause animation and freeze sound.
[4 or R] -> Glitch cutting.
[5 or T] -> Add Colors, glitch cutting and Notes at your own risk :) 
[6 or Y] -> (remove all texts)  
[7 or A] -> Restart with sound ON

metadata.name: The Beauty of Discord #192
metadata.description:
This experimental artwork is a unique blend of human and machine inputs, showcasing the potential for collaboration between the two in the creative process. The human component of the piece is evident in the deliberate composition, choice of color, and the use of painting algorithms. Meanwhile, the machine component is represented by two powerful AI technologies. The first, ChatGPT3, generated a thought-provoking poem about the galaxies and cosmos, serving as the inspiration for the piece. The second, DALL-E 2, then used this poem as a prompt to create a stunning AI image, bringing the cosmic themes to life in a realistic and captivating way.

The combination of these two AI technologies, along with the human touch in the painting algorithms and composition, creates an artwork that is truly one-of-a-kind. The final product is not only visually stunning, but it also serves as a glimpse into the future of humanity and the possibilities of AI collaboration in art. The artwork is a testament to the beauty that can result from a seemingly discordant combination of human and machine inputs, and it invites us to consider the impact of technology on the creative process and the role of the human artist in the age of AI.

Artist notes:
Press s to download high-res images.
Press a to see the AI-generated image.
Press g to switch back to the paint.

Read more on the medium website:

metadata.name: CHIP #110
metadata.description:
A CHIP is being constructed by using two brushes that are painting on the board through deterministic noise, and then turned squared and pixelated and blended into each other, with colours selected from 21 different colour schemes. How many iterations, and the speed and size of the added parts determines the final composition. 

You can stop the iterations by pressing S, and download the current composition by hitting D, and restart/reload the iterations by pressing R.

Notes
The thumbnail generation takes a while and the render/iterations in non-GPU browser can be quite slow. Chrome/Firefox recommended.
